&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS (LPG):&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On liquefaction,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;petroleum gas changes into a liquid&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;which is called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG)&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;main constituent of LPG&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;butane&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;though it contains&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;smaller amounts of&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;ethane&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;propane&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;also.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;From above it is clear that&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;butane&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the main&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;constituent&amp;nbsp;of LPG&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;LPG is stored in cylinders&lt;/span&gt;. It is mainly used for cooking and hence it is also called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;cooking gas&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and the cylinders containing it are called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;cooking gas cylinders&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;valve provided in the cylinder&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;opened&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;with the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;help of a regulator&lt;/span&gt;; due to a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;decrease in pressure&lt;/span&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;LPG changes into a vapour&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;vapour flows to the burners&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;through a rubber tubing attached to the regulator.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;A sulfur-containing compound&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Ethyl Mercaptan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;added to the LPG for imparting its&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;smell&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;so that its detection in case of leakage becomes easier as&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;LPG is an odourless cooking&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;55px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/quesImage13.png&quot; width=&quot;180px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Advantages of LPG:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a high calorific value fuel (50 kJ/g).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It bums without smoke and is pollutionless.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a neat and clean fuel.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is convenient to store.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gold and silver ores are concentrated by leaching.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;leaching method&lt;/strong&gt;, the ore is treated with a suitable reagent in which ore is soluble but impurities do not. Thus, impurities are removed by filtration.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Among galena (PbS), copper pyrites (CuFeS&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;), cinnabar (HgS) and argentite (Ag&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;S) argentite being silver ore is concentrated by chemical leaching method.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Calamine, which is zinc carbonate, is concentrated by the roasting process.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The concentration of Cinnabar is done by the gravity separation and froth floatation method.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cassiterite, which is a tin ore, is concentrated by gravity separation and magnetic separation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Natural cassiterite is crystalline in nature and extremely difficult to dissolve in acids and bases, so the leaching process is not employed for it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;So, the Leaching method is suitable for the concentration of the &lt;strong&gt;argentite&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;55px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/quesImage13.png&quot; width=&quot;180px&quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;However, Artificial Cassiterite is concentrated by pressure leaching, as it is amorphous in nature.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The tendency of an atom to loose, gain or share electrons in order to complete its ocetet is called as&amp;nbsp;its valency.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Oxygen&amp;nbsp;(O) has atomic no. 8, its electronic configuration is 2,6&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its outermost shell has 6 electrons and it needs only 2 electron to complete its octet ,thereby showing valency of -2.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Talking about Magnesium&amp;nbsp;(Mg)&amp;nbsp;its atomic no. is 12, its electronic configuration is 2,8,2.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its outermost shell shows 2 electrons which can be lost, thus leaving a valency of +2.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In case of Beryllium (Be) its atomic no is 4, electronic configuration is 2,2.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Outermost shell of Be&amp;nbsp;has 2 electron which&amp;nbsp;can be removed giving it a valency of +2.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbon has atomic no 6, electronic configuration 2,4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Outermost shell of C shows 4 electrons ,hence it shares its 4 electrons&amp;nbsp;forming covalent bond having valency 4.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/12/F1_Shraddha_Moh%20Tayyab_21.12.2021_D4.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 461px; height: 214px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Silver halides:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A silver halide (also known as a silver salt) is a chemical compound formed when the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;element silver (Ag)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;reacts with one of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;halogens&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bromine (Br), chlorine (Cl), iodine (I), and fluorine (F) can all mix with silver to produce&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;silver bromide (AgBr), silver chloride (AgCl), silver iodide (AgI)&lt;/span&gt;, and three different types of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;silver fluoride.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They&amp;#39;re known as the silver halides as a group, and they&amp;#39;re typically denoted by&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;AgX.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although the majority of silver halides contain silver atoms with oxidation states of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;+1 (Ag&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;+&lt;/span&gt;),&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;silver halides with oxidation states of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;+2 (Ag&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2+&lt;/span&gt;)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;are also known,
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Silver (II) fluoride is the only one that is stable where Ag is in a +2 oxidation state.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Silver&amp;nbsp;halides are Light-sensitive compounds.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Silver chloride is turns grey from white when exposed to sunlight.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are widely employed in photographic film and paper.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Silver halide crystals in gelatin are coated onto a film base, glass, or paper substrate in photographic film and photographic paper, including graphic art film and paper.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As a protective colloid with adequate physical and chemical properties, gelatin is an essential component of the emulsion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although modern practice employs gelatin without trace materials (such as sulphur), the gelatin may contain trace elements (such as sulphur) that boost the emulsion&amp;#39;s light sensitivity.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Colour intensity of silver halides:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Silver halides, except for silver fluoride, are extremely water-insoluble.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The three most common silver halide compounds have different colours that can be used to identify halide ions in a solution fast.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Silver chloride precipitates as a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;white substance.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;silver bromide is a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;creamy substance.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Silver iodide is a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;yellow substance.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;AgI being yellow&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;when it precipitates has&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;greater colour intensity&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;whereas&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;AgCl being white appears&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to be dull and&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;least colour intensive.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct order of silver halides on the basis of colour intensity is -&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;AgCl &amp;lt; AgBr &amp;lt; Agl&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cathodic reactions&lt;/strong&gt; are reduction reactions that occur at the cathode.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Electrons released by the anodic reactions are consumed at the cathode surface.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The atomic mass of Aluminium = 27 amu&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Electron charge = 1 faraday = 96500Cmol&lt;sup&gt;-1&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;cathodic reaction,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Al&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3+&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ 3e&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;rarr;&amp;nbsp; Al&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3F&amp;nbsp;electricity is required to prepare 27 g of Aluminium&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If&amp;nbsp; 27&amp;nbsp;g aluminum&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;is required&amp;nbsp;3F&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;electricity&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;So, 1g aluminum&amp;nbsp;is required = 3&amp;times; 96500/ 27&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, 5120 g aluminum required = 3&amp;times; 96500&amp;times; 5120/ 27&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;5.49&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 10&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;7&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;C&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;5.49&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 10&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;7&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;C.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Ethanol + Methanol​.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ethanol + Methanol​&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;denatured alcohol.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Denatured alcohol&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;ethanol&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;that has additives to make it&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;poisonous, bad-tasting, foul-smelling, or nauseating&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;to discourage its&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;recreational consumption.&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The term&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;denatured alcohol&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;refers to&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;alcohol products adulterated with toxic and/or bad tasting additives&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;(e.g., methanol, benzene, pyridine, castor oil, gasoline, isopropyl alcohol, and acetone), making it unsuitable for&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;human consumption&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The most common additive used is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;methanol (5&amp;ndash;10%)&lt;/span&gt;, giving rise to the term&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;methylated spirits.&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Denatured alcohol is used as a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;lower-cost solvent or fuel for home-scale or industrial use.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Denatured alcohol&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;ethanol or grain alcohol&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;that contains&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;additional chemicals&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;called&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;denaturants&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;that make it unfit for&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;human consumption.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Denatured alcohol&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is fine for some&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;types of lab work&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and as an ingredient in certain products, but it&amp;#39;s&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;not safe to drink&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Ethanol&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;organic chemical compound&lt;/span&gt;. It is simple&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;alcohol&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;with the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;chemical formula C₂H₆O.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its formula can be also written as&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;CH&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&amp;minus;CH&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&amp;minus;OH or C&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;H&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;5&lt;/span&gt;OH&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;and is often abbreviated as&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;EtOH&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Alcohol&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;(ethanol or ethyl alcohol) is the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;ingredient found in beer, wine, and spirits&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;that causes&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;drunkenness&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Alcohol&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is formed when&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;yeast ferments&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;(breaks down without oxygen) the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;sugars in different food&lt;/span&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Egg White &amp;lt; Antacid &amp;lt; Caustic Soda 4 percent (NaOH)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;pH:&lt;/strong&gt; The degree of acidity or alkalinity is a measurement of the hydrogen ion concentration in a solution is known as pH.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Egg White &amp;lt; Antacid &amp;lt; Caustic Soda 4 percent (NaOH)&lt;/strong&gt; is correct with respect to &lt;strong&gt;increasing pH levels.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Egg White:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The initial &lt;strong&gt;pH of egg white is as low as&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;7&lt;/strong&gt;, making it naturally alkaline and it is one of the few food products that are naturally alkaline.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The egg whites are a high-protein food. Due to their low acidic content, they are a good choice for heartburn relief.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Antacid:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Antacids are a type of medicine that works by neutralizing stomach acid and relieving indigestion and heartburn. They contain alkalizing ingredients like calcium, aluminum, sodium bicarbonate, or magnesium which act as bases (alkalis) to neutralize stomach acid.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;pH level of an antacid&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;10&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Caustic Soda 4 percent (NaOH):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;pH of Caustic Soda 4 percent (NaOH)&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;13&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sodium hydroxide is another name for caustic soda. It&amp;#39;s a chemical compound with the formula NaOH.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;4 percent NaOH (sodium hydroxide) means 4 grams of NaOH are dissolved in 100 milliliters of solution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Litmus solution&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is derived from&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Lichen&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Lichen&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is used to determine the solution is neutral/acidic/basic. It has a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;mauve (purple)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;colour in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;distilled water&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When added to an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;acidic solution&lt;/span&gt;, it turns&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;red&lt;/span&gt;. When added to a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;basic solution&lt;/span&gt;, it turns&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;blue&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Lichens&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;plants&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;that belong to the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Thallophyta group&lt;/span&gt;. To obtain a litmus solution, the crushing and grinding of lichens are done. The dyes are then added to neutral water to get the required litmus solution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Litmus solution&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is obtained from&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;lichens&lt;/span&gt;. A natural&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;dye extracted&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;from lichens is dissolved in distilled water to obtain a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;litmus solution&lt;/span&gt;. For example, It is used as an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;indicator to distinguish between acids and bases&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Litmus solution is a purple dye&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;, which is extracted from&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;lichen&lt;/span&gt;, a plant belonging to the division Thallophyta, and is commonly used as an indicator.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are many other natural materials like&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;red cabbage leaves, turmeric, coloured petals&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of some flowers such as&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Hydrangea, Petunia, and Geranium&lt;/span&gt;, which indicate the presence of acid or base in a solution. These are called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;acid-base indicators&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;or sometimes simply indicators.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Most of the acid-base indicators that are commonly used are synthetic but nature has its own indicators.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Hydrangea, petunia, and Geranium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;have the ability to act as indicators&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); width: 300px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Indicator&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Description&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;China Rose&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;It turns acidic solutions to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;dark pink or magenta colour&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and basic solutions to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;green colour.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Phenolphthalein&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;It is an organic compound of the phthalein family that is widely used as an acid-base indicator.&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;As indicator phenolphthalein is colourless below pH 8.5 and attains&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;pink to deep red&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;hue above pH 9.0.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Turmeric&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Turmeric is yellow in acid &amp;amp; neutral substance but turns bright&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;red with bases&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Hydrogen bonding is responsible for which of the following unusual properties of water?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. Its existence in liquid state over a wide range of one hundred degrees (273 K to 373 K).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. High heat of fusion and vaporization.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. Its solid form (ice) being heavier than liquid water.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct code:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hydrogen bond&amp;nbsp;is a&lt;strong&gt; bond between H and highly electronegative elements like Fluorine, Nitrogen and Oxygen.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Due to hydrogen bond, the water acquires&lt;strong&gt; unusual properties &lt;/strong&gt;such as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Cohesion, Adhesion, high thermal conductivity, high freezing and boiling point, High surface tension, high specific heat, High Heat of vaporization, and the fact that ice floats&lt;/strong&gt; (Ice is less dense as a solid than liquid water).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Heat of fusion&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the amount of heat required &lt;strong&gt;to melt the frozen solvent.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Heat of vaporisation&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the amount of enthalpy (heat energy) that is required to transform a &lt;strong&gt;liquid substance into a gas &lt;/strong&gt;or vapour.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Water has a high value of enthalpy of fusion and vaporisation due to formation of hydrogen bonds, as more energy would be required to break the additional bonds.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/01/F1_Utkarsha_Ravi_04.01.21_D1.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alcohols react with sodium leading to the evolution of hydrogen.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;e.g.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;2Na + 2CH&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;CH&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;OH&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;🡪 2CH&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;CH&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;O&amp;ndash;Na (Sodium ethoxide) + H&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;(g)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;reaction&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;alcohols&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;with&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;sodium&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;metal, bond&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;cleavage&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;O - H&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;bond takes place.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;ease&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;breakage&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;the O-H bond&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;alcohols&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is an&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;indication&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;acidity&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;alcohols&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;CH3CH2OH + Na = CH3CH2O-Na+ + H2 | Ethanol and Sodium Reaction&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/01/F1_Utkarsha_15.1.21_Pallavi_D13.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 410px; height: 157px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We know that the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;ease&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of this&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;bond breakage&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;follows the order&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;primary &amp;gt; secondary &amp;gt; tertiary&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, the ease of reactivity of sodium follow the order&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img alt=&quot;Alcohols react with active metals e.g., Na, K etc., to give corres&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/01/F1_Utkarsha_15.1.21_Pallavi_D14.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 83px; width: 330px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The acidity of alcohols:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Just as&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;metals&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;react&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;with acids&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;liberate hydrogen&lt;/span&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;alcohols&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;react with&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;metals&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to liberate&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;hydrogen&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;acting as an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;acid&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;conjugate base&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;alkoxide ion formed after&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;alcohol&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;releases a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;proton&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;R -O&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;-&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;stability&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;conjugate&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;base&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;depends&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;on the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;+I&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;alkyl group R&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;attached because it is&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;not&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;resonance stabilized here.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The strength of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;negative charge&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;increases&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;as we move on from&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;primary&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;secondary&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;tertiary&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;alcohols because of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;number&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;alkyl&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;groups&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;increases&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;increase&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;negative&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;charge over the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;oxygen&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;atom&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;destabilizes&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;conjugate base&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;acidity&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;of&amp;nbsp;alcohols follows the order&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Primary&amp;gt; Secondary &amp;gt; Tertiary&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Alcohols are acidic in nature because hydrogen is attached to oxyg&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/01/F1_Utkarsha_15.1.21_Pallavi_D12.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 204px; width: 373px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rutherford&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;alpha;-particle scattering experiment:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In 1911, Rutherford performed a scattering experiment in which he bombarded thin foils of metals like Gold, silver, platinum or copper with a beam of moving&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;alpha;-particles.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The source of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;alpha;-particles was radium, a radioactive substance, placed in a block of lead. Slits were used to get a fine beam.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The presence of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;alpha;-particle at any point around the thin foil of gold after striking it was detected with the help of a circular zinc sulphide screen. the point at which &amp;alpha;-particle strikes, a flash of light is given out.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_J.K_8.05.2020_Shashi_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 200px; width: 573px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conclusions of Rutherford&amp;#39;s experiment:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Most of the space inside the atom is emp&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;ty because most of the &amp;alpha;-particles passed through the gold foil without getting deflected.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Very few particles were deflected from their path, indicating that the positive charge of the atom occupies very little space.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;A very small fraction of &amp;alpha;-particles were deflected by very large angles, indicating that all the positive charge and mass of the gold atom were concentrated in a very small volume within the atom.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;On the basis of his experiment,&amp;nbsp;Rutherford put forward the model of an atom, which had the following features:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;There is a positively charged centre in an atom called the nucleus. Nearly all the mass of an atom resides in the nucleus.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;margin-bottom: 0cm; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The electrons revolve around the nucleus in well-defined orbits.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;margin-bottom: 0cm; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The size of the nucleus is very small as compared to the size of the atom.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;margin-bottom: 0cm;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;Rutherford&amp;#39;s alpha particle scattering experiment shows the presence of a nucleus in the atom. It also gives the following important information about the nucleus of an atom:​&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;margin-bottom: 0cm;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Nucleus of an atom is &lt;strong&gt;positively charged&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;margin-bottom: 0cm; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;line-height: 1.6;&quot;&gt;Nucleus of an atom is very &lt;strong&gt;dense and hard&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;margin-bottom: 0cm; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nucleus&lt;/strong&gt; of an atom is &lt;strong&gt;very small&lt;/strong&gt; as compared to the size of the atom as a whole.&amp;nbsp;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;margin-bottom: 0cm; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The atom is indivisible and indestructible is given by&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Dalton&amp;#39;s Atomic Theory.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Dalton&amp;#39;s Atomic Theory:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;margin: 0.5em 0px 1em 2.5em; -webkit-font-smoothing: subpixel-antialiased; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); border: 0px; outline: 0px; list-style-position: initial; list-style-image: initial;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;-webkit-font-smoothing: subpixel-antialiased; padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 0.5em; vertical-align: baseline; background: transparent; border: 0px; outline: 0px;&quot;&gt;Dalton&amp;rsquo;s atomic theory proposed that all matter was composed of atoms, indivisible and indestructible building blocks. While all atoms of an element were identical, different elements had atoms of differing sizes and mass.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;-webkit-font-smoothing: subpixel-antialiased; padding: 0px; margin: 0.5em 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: transparent; border: 0px; outline: 0px;&quot;&gt;Dalton&amp;rsquo;s atomic theory also stated that all compounds were composed of combinations of these atoms in defined ratios.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;-webkit-font-smoothing: subpixel-antialiased; padding: 0px; margin: 0.5em 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: transparent; border: 0px; outline: 0px;&quot;&gt;Dalton also postulated that chemical reactions resulted in the rearrangement of the reacting atoms.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;-webkit-font-smoothing: subpixel-antialiased; padding: 0px; margin: 0.5em 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: transparent; border: 0px; outline: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The atom is indivisible and indestructible is not concluded by Rutherford&amp;#39;s&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;alpha;-particle scattering experiment.&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flux&lt;/strong&gt;: The substance which is added to remove the gangue from the concentrated ore in its molten state is called Flux and the substance formed with flux is called Slag. Slags are generally silicates.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Limestone decomposes to give CaO and CO2.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
CaCO3 &amp;rarr; CaO + CO2&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The resultant lime (CaO) acts as flux, combines with silica (present as impurity - gangue) to form calcium silicate (fusible slag).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
CaO&amp;nbsp;+ SiO2 &amp;rarr; CaSiO3 (slag)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flux used in the extraction of iron&lt;/strong&gt; from hematite is &lt;strong&gt;calcium oxide (CaO)&lt;/strong&gt; to remove impurities like SiO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;According to Thomson&amp;#39;s model of an atom:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. An atom consists of a positively charged sphere and the electrons are embedded in it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. The negative and positive charges are not always equal in magnitude. So, the atom as a whole is not always electrically neutral.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct code:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;J.J. Thomson&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;(1856- 1940), a British physicist, was born in Cheetham Hill, a suburb of Manchester, on 18 December 1856.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Thomson&amp;#39;s model of an atom&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thomson proposed the model of an atom to be similar to that of a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Christmas pudding&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;electrons&lt;/span&gt;, in a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;sphere of positive charge&lt;/span&gt;, were like currants (dry fruits) in a spherical Christmas pudding.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One can also think of a watermelon, the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;positive charge&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the atom is&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;spread all over&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;like the red edible part of the watermelon, while the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;electrons are&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;studded in the positively charged sphere&lt;/span&gt;, like the seeds in watermelon.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Thomson proposed that:&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An atom consists of a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;positively charged sphere evenly distributed all over the atom&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;and the electrons are embedded in it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;negative&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;positive charges&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;equal in magnitude&lt;/span&gt;. So, the atom as a whole is&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;electrically neutral.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although Thomson&amp;rsquo;s model explained that atoms are electrically neutral, the results of experiments carried out by other scientists could not be explained by this model.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Image result for plum pudding model&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/03/F1_Puja%20J_26.2.21_Pallavi_D8.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 304px; height: 161px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;Hence, according to the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Thomson model&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;of the atom,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;the positive charge is evenly distributed all over the atom&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rutherford Model of atom:-
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;There is a positively charged center in an atom called the nucleus.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Nearly all the mass of an atom resides in the nucleus.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The electrons revolve around the nucleus in well-defined orbits.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rutherford&amp;#39;s model of the atom is also called the&amp;nbsp;Nuclear model of the atom.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CaCO&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; (s)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Ca(OH)&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; (aq) + CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; (g) &amp;rarr; CaCO&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; (s) + H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O (I)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This reaction is an example of a &lt;strong&gt;neutralization reaction&lt;/strong&gt; in which a base reacts with an acid&amp;nbsp;to produce salt&amp;nbsp;and water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is a balanced equation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;Ca(OH)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;(&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;calcium hydroxide)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;reacts with &lt;span style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; gas (&lt;/span&gt;carbon dioxide), an insoluble milky white precipitate of &lt;span style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;CaCO&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;(calcium carbonate) and &lt;span style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;H&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;O&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;(water) is formed. A double displacement reaction follows the reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CaCO&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;(calcium carbonate) is &lt;strong&gt;basic in nature&lt;/strong&gt; because it is a metal carbonate, which is always basic.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When an acid reacts with a &lt;strong&gt;metal carbonate or metal hydrogen carbonate&lt;/strong&gt;, it gives the &lt;strong&gt;corresponding&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;salt, carbon dioxide gas, and water.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Na&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;HCO&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;  position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;+ HCl&amp;nbsp;&amp;rarr;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;NaCl + H&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;  position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;O + CO&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;  position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Uses of sodium hydrogen carbonate (NaHCO&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For making baking powder, which is a mixture of baking soda (sodium hydrogen carbonate) and a mild edible acid such as tartaric acid. When baking powder is heated or mixed in water, the following reaction takes place &amp;ndash;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;NaHCO3+ H&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;+&lt;/span&gt;&amp;rarr; CO2+ H2O + Sodium salt of an acid.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Carbon dioxide produced during the reaction causes bread or cake to rise to make them soft and spongy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sodium hydrogen carbonate is also an ingredient in antacids.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Being alkaline, it neutralizes excess acid in the stomach and provides relief.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is also used in soda-acid fire extinguishers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Bleaching powder is used:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For bleaching cotton and linen in the textile industry, for bleaching the wood pulp in paper factories and for bleaching washed clothes in the laundry.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;As an oxidizing agent in many chemical industries.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For disinfecting drinking water to make it free of germs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Uses of washing soda:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sodium carbonate (washing soda) is used in glass, soap and paper industries.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;It is used in the manufacture of sodium compounds such as borax.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sodium carbonate can be used as a cleaning agent for domestic purposes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is used for removing the permanent hardness of the water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;FREE RADICALS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Free radicals are species having neutral carbon in which there is three bond pairs and one unshared electron.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Carbon free radicals are generally sp&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;hybridized as the unpaired electron of carbon is not generally involved in hybridization.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;STABILITY OF CARBON FREE RADICALS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Stability of free radicals mainly depends upon the &lt;strong&gt;resonance effect &lt;/strong&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;hyperconjugation&lt;/strong&gt;. The inductive effect has a very little role in stability of free radicals.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/08/F1_Utkarsha_Ravi_10.08.21_D2.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 794px; height: 156px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The stability order of free radicals&amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;3&lt;sup&gt;0&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;gt; 2&amp;nbsp;&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;gt; 1&lt;sup&gt;0&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;gt; Methyl &lt;/strong&gt;can be explained on the basis of inductive effect also on the basis of hyperconjugation effect.&amp;nbsp;Whereas the stability of allyl and benzyl free radicals is due to resonance.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Benzyl and allyl free radicals are more stable due to the resonance or delocalization of free electrons&lt;/strong&gt;. Whereas &lt;strong&gt;benzyl free radical is more stable than allyl due to the greater number of resonating structures.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The stability of given free radicals are in the order&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\((CH_3)_2 \dot CH &amp;lt; (CH_3)_3 \dot C &amp;lt; (C_6H_5)_2 \dot CH &amp;lt; (C_6 H_5)_3 \dot C\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Benzyl and allyl free radicals are more stable due to resonance or delocalization of free electrons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The more the number of resonating structures is more is the stability of benzylic free radicals.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\left( {{C_6}{H_5}} \right)_3}\mathop C\limits^ \bullet \)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; has more resonating structures than&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\left( {{C_6}{H_5}} \right)_2}\mathop {CH}\limits^ \bullet \)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; , hence&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\left( {{C_6}{H_5}} \right)_3}\mathop C\limits^ \bullet \)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is more stable than benzyl free radicle.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On the basis of hyperconjugation effect,&amp;nbsp;The stability order of free radicals is given as&amp;nbsp; 3&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;0&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;gt; 2&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;0&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;gt; 1&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;0&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;gt; Methyl.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Concept&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When atoms are excited they&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;emit light of certain wavelengths&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;that correspond to different colours&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;due to the electron&amp;nbsp;making&amp;nbsp;transitions&amp;nbsp;between two&amp;nbsp;energy levels&amp;nbsp;in an atom.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;wavelength&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;related to these emissions is&amp;nbsp;given by the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Rydberg formula.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;energy differences between levels in the Bohr model&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are given by the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Rydberg formula.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;wavelengths of emitted/absorbed photons&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\displaystyle {1 \over λ }=Z^{2}R_{H }\left({1 \over {n_{1}}^{2}}-{1 \over {n_{2}}^{2}}\right)}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.42857;&quot;&gt;Given that atom is hydrogen so Z = 1;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.42857;&quot;&gt;It is excited from ground state n&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 1 to third orbit&amp;nbsp;n&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;= 3&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where Z&amp;nbsp;is the&amp;nbsp;atomic number, n&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;the lower energy level orbit, n&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the upper energy level orbit, and R&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is the&amp;nbsp;Rydberg constant (1.09677 &amp;times; 10&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;7&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;m&lt;sup&gt;&amp;minus;1&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;for hydrogen and&amp;nbsp;1.09737 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;7&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;m&lt;sup&gt;&amp;minus;1&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;for heavy metals).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;wavelength for ionization&lt;/strong&gt; is given by:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\displaystyle {1 \over λ }=Z^{2}R_{∞ }\left({1 \over {n_{1}}^{2}}-{1 \over {n_{2}}^{2}}\right)}\)&lt;/span&gt;; where R&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt; = Rydberg&amp;#39;s constant&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Z= atomic number is 1 for H-atom, n&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 1, and n&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; =&amp;nbsp;&amp;infin;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the wavelength now becomes:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\displaystyle {1 \over λ }=1^{2}R_{∞ }\left({1 \over {1}^{2}}-{1 \over \infty ^{2}}\right)}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\displaystyle {1 \over λ }=1^{2}R}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;or,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;R&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;lambda; = 1, we know that h&amp;times;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nu; = energy, so multiplying both sides with h&amp;nu; we get:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;h&amp;nu; = E = R&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;lambda;&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; h&amp;nu;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We know that&amp;nbsp;&amp;nu; =&amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;frequency of light = c/&amp;lambda;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence,&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( R_Hλ × hν = {R_H\lambda hc\over \lambda} = R_Hhc\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the expression for &lt;strong&gt;ionisation enthalpy of a hydrogen atom &lt;/strong&gt;in terms of Rydberg&amp;rsquo;s constant (R&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;H&lt;/span&gt;) &lt;strong&gt;is&amp;nbsp;hCR&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;H&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Ionization potential (I.P)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;energy&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;required to take out&amp;nbsp;the outermost electron from an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;isolated gaseous&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;atom.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The ionization energy of a chemical element is expressed in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;kiloJoules&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;or&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;electron volts&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The energy required to remove the first electron is called the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1st ionization potential.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Water vapour.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrogen is a chemical element&lt;/strong&gt; with the symbol &amp;#39;H,&amp;#39; atomic number 1, and an atomic mass of 1.008. Hydrogen is the &lt;strong&gt;lightest element in the periodic table.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When &lt;strong&gt;hydrogen is burned, it goes through a chemical reaction&lt;/strong&gt;. In this chemical reaction, hydrogen combines with oxygen to form water, &lt;strong&gt;releasing a significant amount of energy.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2H&lt;sub&gt;2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;+ O&lt;sub&gt;2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;rarr; 2H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O + energy&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When hydrogen burns, it produces a lot of energy. And the majority of the energy is released as heat. Gases expand as a result of the heat.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;And the &lt;strong&gt;reaction produces hydrogen, oxygen, and water vapour&lt;/strong&gt; as a gaseous mixture.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although&lt;strong&gt; water vapour is the most abundant greenhouse gas &lt;/strong&gt;in the atmosphere, other greenhouse gases also exist (such as carbon dioxide and methane).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The heat emitted by the Earth&amp;#39;s surface is absorbed by water vapour molecules in the lower atmosphere.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;water vapour&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; is emitted when hydrogen is burned.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Concept:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The element Silicon (Si) is the&amp;nbsp;member of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;group 14&amp;nbsp;or IV A.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;silicon is used extensively as a semiconductor in solid-state devices in the computer and microelectronics industries.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Silicon has 14 electrons total.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The electronic configuration of Silicon&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1s&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;2s&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;2p&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3s&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;3p&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;So, silicon has &lt;strong&gt;4 valence electrons.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/18/10/Electrician_23_15Q_Basic%20Electricity_Hindi%20-%20Final_images_q9.PNG&quot; style=&quot;height: 143px; width: 143px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence we can conclude that&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4 electrons&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;are present in outermost shell of Silicon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​3 electrons are present in outermost shell of Aluminium (Al).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;1 electron present in outermost shell of Sodium (Na).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;2 electrons are present in outermost shell of M&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;agnesium (Mg).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;background-color:  (255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; &quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1808&lt;/span&gt;, &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;John Dalton&lt;/span&gt; first proposed an &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;atomic theory of matter&lt;/span&gt; and he named it Dalton&amp;#39;s atomic theory. Dalton&amp;rsquo;s atomic theory was able to explain the law of conservation of mass, law of constant composition, and law of multiple proportions very successfully.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dalton&amp;rsquo;s Atomic Theory:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;background-color:  (255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The smallest indivisible particle of matter is called an atom.&lt;/span&gt; The theory states that all the matter is composed of indestructible and indivisible building blocks called atoms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All atoms of a &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;specific element are identical in mass, size, and other properties.&lt;/span&gt; However, atoms of different elements exhibit different properties and vary in mass and size.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Atoms can neither be created nor destroyed.&lt;/span&gt; Furthermore, atoms cannot be divided into smaller particles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Atoms of different elements can &lt;strong&gt;combine&lt;/strong&gt; with each other in fixed &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;whole-number ratios&lt;/span&gt; in order to form compounds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Atoms can be rearranged, combined, or separated in chemical reactions.​&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; &quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;background-color:  (255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Law of conservation of mass:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;According to the law, &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;mass&lt;/span&gt; can &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;neither be destroyed nor be created&lt;/span&gt; in any chemical reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Law of constant proportion/ definite proportion:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The laws state that in a chemical substance, the elements are &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;always present in certain proportions by mass&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;For example&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;/div&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Oxygen &amp;amp; Hydrogen&lt;/span&gt; are present in water in a ratio of&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt; 8:1&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;So we will obtain &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1g of hydrogen&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;8g of oxygen &lt;/span&gt;if we &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;decompose 9g of water&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Atom:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An atom is the &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;smallest invisible&lt;/span&gt; unit of matter &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;that constitutes&lt;/span&gt; a chemical element.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Every &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;plasma, solid, gas &amp;amp; liquid&lt;/span&gt;, is composed of &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;ionized or neutral atoms&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Around &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;100 picometers&lt;/span&gt; across, atoms are extremely small.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following types of inter molecular interactions or forces is/are called van der Waals forces?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. London forces&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. Dipole - dipole forces&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. Dipole - induced dipole forces&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;4. Hydrogen bonding&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct code:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Intermolecular forces are forces of attraction and repulsion between interacting molecules.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vander Waal forces are very short-lived forces weak forces &lt;/strong&gt;and exist between all molecules when they are quite close to each other.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Vander Waal forces are of three types namely London forces, dipole-dipole forces, dipole induced dipole force.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A) London forces:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Observed in &lt;strong&gt;non-polar molecules&lt;/strong&gt; like H&lt;sub&gt;2,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;F&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, Cl&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Weakest of all intermolecular forces.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At a particular point of time, the distribution of electrons gets shifted towards one side causing&lt;strong&gt; temporary separation of positive and negative charge&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B) Dipole-dipole forces:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Molecules have&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;permanent dipole moment.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In polar molecule centre&amp;nbsp;of positive and negative charge do not coincide and the ends&lt;strong&gt; possess partial charges.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When such molecules come close to each other &lt;strong&gt;they orient themself in a manner that results in an attraction &lt;/strong&gt;between these dipoles.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C) Dipole induced dipole forces:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Observed in mixture containing&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Polar and non-polar molecules.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When non-polar molecules come close to polar molecules the positive ends of polar molecules attract electrons of non-polar molecules thus leading to a separation of charge in nonpolar molecules which is referred to as induced dipole.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Concept:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The substance which along with water are used for cleaning or for removing dirt are known as detergents. Soaps has been used as detergent for many years, but they are different. They are synthetic detergent or soapless detergent or simply detergent.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Soap:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;A soap is the sodium or potassium salt of a long chain carboxylic acid or glycerol.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;They are prepared from animal fats or plant based oils.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Their efficiency decreases in hard water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;It take more time to dissolve in water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;They are biodegradable.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Synthetic Detergent or soapless soap:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;They are the sodium salts of long chain benzene sulphonic acids or the sodium salt of a long chain alkyl hydrogen sulphate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;They are prepared from hydrocarbons extracted from coal or petroleum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Their efficiency is unaffected in hard water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;They dissolve faster than soaps.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Some are not biodegradable&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Medicated soaps&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;contain antibacterial properties to care for your skin. By removing all the bacteria that generally cause skin issues, medical&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;soap&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;helps to treat your skin gently.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Toilet soap&lt;/strong&gt; is also a soap used for skins and based on animal or plant oils.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Glycerine soap&lt;/strong&gt; contains more glycerine which is gentler to skin and which is animal or plant oils.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Laundry soap are a synthetic detergent&lt;/strong&gt; and used for cleaning cloths which is unaffected by hard or soft water.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Since laundry soap is synthetic detergent it is soapless soap.&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Double Displacement Reaction:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The reaction in which both &lt;strong&gt;cation &lt;/strong&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;anion &lt;/strong&gt;are displaced to the products is called a double displacement reaction.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;​&amp;nbsp;Eg: AgNO&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; + NaCl &amp;rarr; AgCl + NaNO&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A displacement reaction is also known as a&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;replacement reaction or a metathesis reaction.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Single Displacement:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The reaction in which &lt;strong&gt;cation or anion from the reactant side &lt;/strong&gt;is displaced to the products is called displacement reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Eg: Fe + CuSO&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;rarr; FeSO&lt;sub&gt;4 &lt;/sub&gt;+ Cu.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Metals of &lt;strong&gt;high reactivity displace&lt;/strong&gt; the metals of&lt;strong&gt; low reactivity from their anions&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rancidity:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rancidity is a process of complete or&lt;strong&gt; incomplete oxidation of food&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is the development of unpleasant smells oils, which are often accompanied by changes in their texture and appearance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are two types of rancidity- Hydrolytic and oxidative.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Corrosion:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Corrosion is a process of &lt;strong&gt;oxidation of metals&lt;/strong&gt; to form their &lt;strong&gt;stable oxides and hydroxides&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Corrosion &lt;/strong&gt;takes place due to &lt;strong&gt;exposure of the metal surface to water or moisture&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When &lt;strong&gt;copper is corroded&lt;/strong&gt; it changes its &lt;strong&gt;colour to reddish-brown and finally green&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Non-metals:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Elements which don&amp;#39;t show any metallic character and properties are said as non-metals.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Properties of Non-metals:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Non-metals are dull in appearance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are brittle and thus, shatter when hammered.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are bad conductors of heat and electricity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They don&amp;#39;t show the property of ductility, which means they can&amp;#39;t be drawn into wires.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are not malleable or can&amp;#39;t be changed into sheets.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have low densities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can be solid, liquid or gas at room temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They don&amp;#39;t produce rich sound when hit on any surface or they are not sonorous.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Non-metals do not react with acids.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are generally light in weight.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Non-metal oxides are molecular substances that form acidic solutions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They tend to form anions of oxyanions in an aqueous solution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They do not have any lustre or shine in themselves.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Oxides of non-metals are acidic in nature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Non-metal oxides react with bases and form the salt.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Examples of non-metal:&amp;nbsp;Hydrogen, Chlorine, Nitrogen, Carbon, etc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/05/F4_Madhuri_Teaching_17.05.2022_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 433px; height: 319px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Matchstick heads.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The modern safety match was developed only about two centuries ago.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On the head of a suitable wood match, a mixture of antimony trisulphide, potassium chlorate, and white phosphorus, along with some glue and starch, was applied.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The heat of friction ignited white phosphorus when it was struck against a rough surface.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This started the combustion of the match.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;White phosphorus, on the other hand, proved to be hazardous to both workers in the match industry and users.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Nowadays, &lt;strong&gt;the head of a safety match is made up of only antimony trisulphide and potassium chlorate.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The rubbing surface contains powdered glass and a trace of red phosphorus (which is much less dangerous).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some red phosphorus is converted to white phosphorus when the match is struck against the rubbing surface.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This immediately reacts with potassium chlorate in the matchstick head, producing enough heat to ignite antimony trisulphide and begin the combustion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
